article.headline: Late free throws preserve Lady Razorbacks' win
article.linkText: Arkansas holds off late rally from No. 24 Oregon
article.story:
FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Free throws in the closing seconds by Sarah Pfeifer and Rochelle Vaughn -- and a blocked shot by Sheree Thompson -- allowed Arkansas to overcome a furious comeback by Oregon and escape with a 65-62 victory Tuesday night.

Arkansas (9-1) led 31-15 at the half and by as much as 18 points early in the second half.

But after a timeout with 11:20 left in the game and Arkansas up 45-28, Oregon (7-2) went on a 17-2 run to get within wto points, 47-45, with just under five minutes remaining.

The Ducks never got the lead but never trailed by more than seven points thereafter, getting with a single point, 63-62, with 28.8 seconds on the clock.

Pfeifer then sank a free throw -- the second of two, after missing the first. A steal by Arkansas' Danielle Allen meant Oregon had to foul to stop the clock, and Vaughn went to the line and made a foul shot with 11.7 seconds remaining, putting the Lady Razorbacks up 65-62.

With one second showing on the clock, Thompson blocked a shot by Oregon's Kristin Forristall to preserve the victory.

The Ducks' Cathrine Kraayeveld led all scorers with 20 points, while Forristall added 10.

Only three Lady Razorbacks scored 10 points or more, with Ruby Vaden topping the Arkansas scoring with 12 points. Vaughn scored 11 points, and Kristin People added 10.

Arkansas hit only 32 percent of its field-goal attempts, while Oregon's shooting was a bit better at 40 percent.
